@{b}
Introduction
------------
@{ub}
  Firstly, we (Stian and I) would like to take the opportunity to thank all of 
you who supported us during the development of Interplay. Everyone who sent us 
bug-reports, ideas, letters, emails and all the positive response all deserve
a big Thank You. It was all the response on our releases that kept us going, 
and without that, we might have stopped with the first version. But we didn't, 
and officially we made around 7 releases. 


@{b}
History of "CD Player" -> "Interplay"
-------------------------------------
@{ub}
  The story of Interplay is quite funny actually. It started when Stian and I 
bought a RPG CD where you played by skipping tracks back and forth to decide 
where to go and what do to. The game was called Track of the Vampire and had 
about 50 tracks or so if I remember correctly. Of course, playing this game on 
the livingroom-stereo forced me to sit in front of the cdplayer and stare into 
the display while listening. That was not comfortable (I did finish the game 
though) and I got my hands on the CD32 developers kit from a guy and found all 
the information on the cd.device which I gave to Stian telling him that we 
ought to make a short player with a slider for track-selection in order for 
us to play Track of the Vampire with slightly more comfort :)

  This was the beginning of our first program called "CD Player V1.0". I made
a GUI in GadToolsBox and we were off. Stian kept on programming and I added 
stuff to the GUI, so we kind of drove each others into making more details on 
the player. Nevertheless, the CD Player was released as "CD Player V1.0" and 
we got alot of feedback from people who claimed it was the best player around. 
Therefore we went on developing the software. Another source that drove us was 
that there wasn't made a proper cdplayer for the amiga that had support for the
Overdrive/Zappo CD-Rom system from Archos (french company). The program grew, 
and our success was based on a small detail called "cd recognition" that we 
developed. This had the program remember the CD's in order to bring back  
information the user had assigned for that specific CD. I have been watching 
the flow of new cdplayers for the amiga lately, and I can see that almost all
players of today have CD Recognition. 

  Then Interplay was born. We had to find a new name for the player since
"CD Player" was such a lame name. Actually, it wasn't a name at all, just a 
prototype nick. Eventually, we came up with Interplay which can mean 
"an cooperation between two or more persons". The name sounded nice, and the
word itself had a meaning, so that was the birth of Interplay. (Keep in mind
that we hadn't heard of the PC company Interplay(tm) when we thought of 
Interplay as our program-name. We found out later).

  The GUI was expanded throughout the versions and the sourcecode grew from
small to BIIG as a result of many new implemented features. Our last release
was Version 4.1 and it looks like that will be the final one. However, the GUI
for Version 5.0 which was meant to be a dual-development is finsihed but due
to technical difficulties, the release of V5.0 won't happen. Ok, I will explain
why. Our thought was to make a doubleversion which consisted of V5.0 and 
V5.0Gold where the gold version had a much nicer GUI than the V5.0 had. Both
GUI's are ready, but we decided that the sourcecode had to be reprogrammed
for several reasons. It would have taken alot of time to finish such a task,
and when Stian was in the army it was difficult for him to program since he
was rarely ever home that year. I brought my amiga to the army and finished
off the Gold GUI there.

@{b}
  ----------------------------------------------------------------------- 
  Look at the file "Interplay5.iff" for a screenshot of how wonderful the
  world could have been :)
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
@{ub}


@{b}
What will happen ?
------------------
@{ub}
  After a long break, it seems now to be pointless to reprogram Interplay and
adapt it to the new GUI's. However, I have included some screenshots from the
various windows from the Gold version for you to look at what you're missing
out on ;) I think there are players out on the net that easily compares to
Interplay and has the functions that Interplay once had. This is why we put
our dear project on ice (for 90 years) and zoom in on other projects that
gives us greater pleasure making instead of reprogramming something we did
in the past. 

@{b}
To contact us
----------
@{ub}
  If you have problems with previous versions of Interplay, feel free to 
contact either of us for help. 
 
    Espen Skog                  Stian Olsen
